events.name: Hangout on Air with Women in Tech
events.description:
This is a watch only event brought to you by Women Techmakers Baltimore 

Watch right from here .....

http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UK-CYYJoS1s

3 women in technology talk about technology at work or school. Janice has been a software engineer for 35 years. She was 16 when she got her first programming job working in Commodore Pet basic. Janice loves the challenge of learning new technology and building beautiful software. Her current adventure is building and managing a scale testing lab, which lets her learn lots of cool new things and have a huge impact for the company's clients.
She is hoping to inspire other women by discussing her career journey from coding on the first PCs, to mainframe development, then client server technology followed by Java/J2EE and these days: ruby, powershell, vmware, and oracle database performance tuning.
She has been very fortunate in her tech career to do many interesting things and to have a lot of flexibility for home and family life.

Gretchen has been working with children and adolescents in the community for over a decade. She holds a BA in philosophy and the history of science and mathematics from St. John's College in Annapolis, and an MS in Applied Psychology from the University of Baltimore. Her work in the non-profit sector has included teaching life skills, building community and fostering self-esteem through the arts, workforce development, and career counseling. Gretchen is co-founder and executive director of Code in the Schools, a non-profit whose mission is to teach under-served and under-represented Baltimore City Students computer programming.

Celeste Lunn
is currently a college Computer Science major and the vice president of the match club of her school. Her technology experience began with working on websites of her high school, where she also managed all
aspects of video and sound, did all server updates and made daily announcements. Last semester she spent abroad in The Netherlands developing and updating websites. It was an amazing experience for her. She wishes to work in that field and is pursuing a career in technology
She loves to share her perspective as a female student in technology, and is very much look forward to gaining advice and wisdom from other experienced Women in Technology .﻿

events.name: Participate at Baltimore's 4th Hackathon

venue.name: The Digital Harbor Foundation Tech Center

events.description:
http://baltimorehackathon.com/

Parking info !!!!

Are you ready yet? We are! Please read this entire email - it is not 140 characters so apologies in advance - important info in here.

Address:

1045 Light Street

Baltimore, MD  21230

GPS may take you to the back of the building but the entrance is located on the corner of Light and Cross Streets.

Parking:

Yep - Parking in the city isn’t ideal but we’ve got several solutions for you:

-Street parking (metered on the main routes, free in the residential areas - be cautious of signs)

-Fed Hill Prep School parking lot. 137 E. Hamburg Street. MUST go into the tech center after parking for a pass to put in your car. Free.

-Digital Harbor High School parking lot. 1100 Covington Street. This is a few blocks away from DHF ~.4 miles. Free.

-West Street Parking Garage - $16/day

Other transportation:

Bike racks in front of DHF

MTA: 064

Charm City Circulator: Purple Route. Cross Street Market stop (323). Light and E. Cross Street

Zip car spots: 1100 Light Street

Uber/Lyft/Use the slack channel to ask for a car pool

This is not a GDG event but a Baltimore Tech Community event.

To participate you will need a ticket 

https://www.eventbrite.com/e/4th-annual-baltimore-hackathon-tickets-18019202921

Your host for this event is Paris Pittman (AOL) and you might know her from sponsoring the event venue for I/O extended.

The 4th Annual Baltimore Hackathon planning is underway for Sept 18-20th. This year they are moving locations, dates, and increasing prize amounts - it’s sure to sell out again.

Last year, they had 110 participants, which was venue capacity, and this year at Digital Habor Foundation plus the use of Federal Hill prep gym, they can accommodate up to 140. They will also utilize themes this year to try to spark ideas early to increase onsite productivity and make it easier for first time participants.

The event is September 18-20th. UA, Stanley Black and Decker, DHF, and the Mayor's Office of IT are already on board. They hope to attract more new folks to the scene and more experience folks with the increase in rewards!

events.name: "Our Time To Lead"
events.description:
"Our Time To Lead" a Women's Day celebration

11.00 am Registration

11.30 am Opening 

11.45 am Keynote Speaker 

Emily Rasowsky, Founder and CEO of All Women in Tech and Director of Marketing Strategy for Social Driver 

Hacking the Definition of 'Women in Tech' 

Have you Googled 'Women in Tech' lately? The results you get aren't so great. We all know this. We've heard this hundreds of time. So why aren't we seeing more movement? Why do we still fall short, even when we try our damnedest to be inclusive. This talk will begin to challenge our definition of 'women in tech' and begin to unpack where we all hold unconscious biases that lead to lack of diversity. We will look at not just the statistics around women in tech but what we can all do to help improve diversity and inclusion of other women at every level of the 'tech world'.  You'll walk away with clear steps on how you can personally move the meter around making a difference for all women in tech.  

12.30 pm Lunch

01.00 pm Network interactive

Mingle Magic : 

Four Best Practices to Achieving your Goals Through Networking ~ Join us for this hands on, information rich workshop where we will explore and practice the essentials of effective networking.  From a "pre game" plan to your post event follow up these tools are guaranteed to put you on the path to success, providing you with the magic you need to mingle with the best of them!

http://www.lisastearns.com/Welcome.html

2.00 Panel

Questions and Answers

events.description:
Exciting news this month! We've teamed up with Praxis Engineering to host our first monthly meetup outside the city!!! This months talks will be at Black Flag Brewing Company in Columbia, MD. Also note that we've moved the day of the week to Tuesday. Doors open at 4:30PM but the talks will start at 5:30PM.

This month we'll be having two talks:

James Starkey from Praxis Engineering will be giving a two part talk on Kubernetes, titled "Kubernetes: Container Orchestration for the Enterprise." 

With the evolution of using container solutions (such as Docker) as the way to do software development, a new problem has come about, Container Sprawl.  Kubernetes is an open source product inspired and informed by Google's experiences and internal systems to manage and coordinate those containers.  We briefly discuss some basics of a Kubernetes system and lessons learned from implementing a Kubernetes cluster.

Cody Henthorne from GDG Baltimore will be giving an introductory talk on hobbyist 3D printing titled, "Printing Your Imagination: 3D Printing 101".

A special thanks to this month's sponsor Praxis Engineering. Praxis is sponsoring the location, food, and drink. Here's a note from them and some of the extra perks the partnership brings our community:

FREE food and drinks will be available throughout the evening along with chances to win one of a few gift cards (Must be present to win)! Bring your friends/colleagues/cubemates out to learn about this exciting topic, as well as, mingle with some of the most talented engineers in the industry!

events.name: WTM Presents: Setting & Achieving Goals
events.description:
Does this cold have you hibernating? Come out and network with other Women Techmakers and start 2018 off right as we welcome Amy Rogers, Development Team Lead at HAVAS helia NA. Amy will share her tips and tricks for setting up achievable goals and sticking with them. We welcome and encourage every gender to attend. As always, we will have food and drinks. Why is goal setting important and not just a silly task?

People with written goals are 50% more likely to achieve them than people without goals. Goal setting and achieving them can appear as a daunting task, but it doesn't have to be. By applying some simple rules to your goal setting process you will be less likely to fail and more likely to find yourself right where you want to be. During this workshop, we will walk through several different types of goal setting and some easy steps to follow to ensure goal setting and achieving success. Your goal isn't too big for you. Your goal isn't wrong for you. You just need to train your brain to make it happen.

events.name: WTM: Optimal Community Engagement with Using Health Technology
events.description:
Please join Women Techmakers Baltimore as we welcome guest speaker, Phylicia Porter, who will be discussing healthcare technology.

As a major urban city and public health hub, Baltimore is on the prepuce of redefining urban telehealth. With the development of the telehealth wellness platform Connect & Thrive, Phylicia shares some key synergistic strategies for community engagement using telehealth platforms. Attendees will learn key strategies for optimal community engagement using emerging telehealth technologies in urban environments.

Phylicia Porter is a public health advocate for health equity, quality education, and a "level playing field" for optimal quality of life regardless of race, creed, and gender among other social and political defining factors. Born and raised in Baltimore MD, Phylicia has participated in various major legislative actions tailored to vulnerable and under-served populations across Maryland and the District of Columbia. As Managing Partner of Optimal Public Health Solutions, Phylicia has established herself and her brand as a solid forerunner and advocate for culturally competent, tailored, and evidenced-based population health change within the city of Baltimore. Her continued passion for the elimination of health disparities has fostered relationships with many community partners and organizations. Phylicia has been affiliated with Battelle Memorial Institute, US Army Public Health Command, US Department of Health and Human Services, University of Maryland School of Medicine, Morgan State University, Towson University, and National Institutes of Health.

While we love to celebrate women in tech, Women Techmakers Baltimore welcomes every gender to attend our events. Our event will start out at 6pm with pizza and mingling and then dive into our topic at 6:30. Hope to see you there!
